{"title_page": "Hard palate", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox anatomy\n| Name        = Hard palate\n| Latin       = palatum durum\n| Image       = Illu mouth.jpg\n| Caption     = Mouth (oral cavity)\n| Image2      = Blausen_0872_UpperRespiratorySystem.png\n| Caption2    = Upper respiratory system, with hard palate labeled at right.\n| Precursor   =\n| System      =\n| Artery      = [[greater palatine artery]]\n| Vein        =\n| Nerve       = [[greater palatine nerve]], [[nasopalatine nerve]]\n| Lymph       =\n}}\n\nThe '''hard palate''' is a thin horizontal [[bone|bony]] plate made up of two bones of the [[facial skeleton]], located in the roof of the mouth. The bones are the [[palatine process of the maxilla]] and the [[horizontal plate of palatine bone]]. The hard palate spans the [[alveolar process|alveolar arch]] formed by the [[alveolar process]] that holds the upper [[teeth]] (when these are developed).\n\n==Structure==\nThe hard palate is formed by the [[palatine process of the maxilla]] and [[horizontal plate of palatine bone]]. It forms a partition between the nasal passages and the [[mouth]]. On the anterior portion of the hard palate are the plicae, irregular ridges in the mucous membrane that help facilitate the movement of food backward towards the larynx. This partition is continued deeper into the mouth by a fleshy extension called the [[soft palate]].\nIt\u2019s sensory innervation is greater palatine nerve and nasopalatine nerve but it\u2019s motor is glossopharyngeal nerve.\n\n==Function==\nThe hard palate is important for feeding and speech. Mammals with a defective hard palate may die shortly after birth due to inability to suckle (see [[#Cleft palate|Cleft palate]] below). It is also involved in [[mastication]] in many species. The interaction between the [[tongue]] and the hard palate is essential in the formation of certain [[Speech communication|speech]] sounds, notably [[palatal consonant]]s such as {{IPA|/j/}} and /t/\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Cleft palate===\nIn the [[birth defect]] called [[cleft palate]], the left and right portions of this plate are not joined, forming a gap between the mouth and nasal passage (a related defect affecting the face is [[cleft lip]]).\n\nWhile a cleft palate has a severe impact upon the ability to [[lactation|nurse]] and speak, it is now successfully treated through reconstructive [[surgery|surgical]] procedures at an early age. This is the time where such procedures are available.\n\nDue to the complexity of this birth defect, researchers still do not know exactly what causes the cleft palate to develop during human development. Recently, these researchers found that even though there is no exact cause, there are several risk factors that drastically increase the risk of a baby being born with an orofacial cleft palate. As for the environmental risk factors, maternal smoking is the most influential risk factor. Based on a recent study of 103 German patients with cleft palates, it was found that 25.2% of them developed the defect due to excessive maternal smoking during pregnancy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reiter |first1=Rudolf |last2=Brosch |first2=Sibylle |last3=Luedeke |first3=Manuel |last4=Fischbein |first4=Elena |last5=Haase |first5=S |last6=Pickhard |first6=A |last7=Assum |first7=G |last8=Schwandt |first8=A |last9=Vogel |first9=W |last10=Maier |first10=C |last11=Hogel |first11=J |title=Genetic and Environmental Risk Factors for Submucous Cleft Palate. |journal=European Journal of Oral Sciences |date=April 2012 |volume=120 |issue=2 |page=97 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0722.2012.00948.x |pmid=22409215 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/221695097 |accessdate=23 November 2019 |ref=4}}</ref> \n\nWhile maternal smoking during pregnancy is a risk, there are also several genetic risk factors. Five SNP variants in the PAX7 gene affect development of facial features.<ref name=Lud2012/> These variations occur at six [[Locus (genetics) | loci]]: 1p36, 2p21, 3p11.1, 8q21.3, 13q31.1 and 15q22.<ref name=Lud2012/> When tested in the European and Asian communities, these loci tests had a 95% acceptance rate.<ref name=Lud2012>{{cite journal |last1=Ludwig |first1=KU |last2=Mangold |first2=E |last3=Herms |first3=S |last4=Nowak |first4=S |last5=Reutter |first5=H |last6=Paul |first6=A |last7=Becker |first7=J |last8=Herberz |first8=R |last9=AlChawa |first9=T |last10=Nasser |first10=E |last11=Bohmer |first11=AC |last12=Mattheisen |first12=M |last13=Alblas |first13=MA |last14=Barth |first14=S |last15=Kluck |first15=N |last16=Lauster |first16=C |last17=Braumann |first17=B |last18=Reich |first18=RH |last19=Hemprich |first19=A |last20=P\u00f6tzsch |first20=S |last21=Blaumeiser |first21=B |last22=Daratsianos |first22=N |last23=Kreusch |first23=T |last24=Murray |first24=JC |last25=Marazita |first25=ML |last26=Ruczinski |first26=I |last27=Scott |first27=AF |last28=Beaty |first28=TH |last29=Kramer |first29=FJ |last30=Wienker |first30=TF |last31=Steegers-Theunissen |first31=RP |last32=Rubini |first32=M |last33=Mossey |first33=PA |last34=Hoffman |first34=P |last35=Lange |first35=C |last36=Chichon |first36=S |last37=Propping |first37=P |last38=Knapp |first38=M |last39=Nothen |first39=MM |title=Genome-wide meta-analyses of nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate identify six new risk loci. |journal=Nat Genet |date=Aug 5, 2012 |volume=44 |issue=9 |page=968 |doi=10.1038/ng.2360 |pmid=22863734 |pmc=3598617 }}</ref>. Besides the PAX 7 gene variants, there were also five possible mutations found in the transforming growth factor- alpha gene or TGFA gene that can lead to the development of a cleft palate <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kohli |first1=Sarvraj Singh |last2=Kohli |first2=Virinder Singh |title=A comprehensive review of the genetic basis of cleft lip and palate |journal=Journal of Oral and Maxillofacial Pathology |date=Jan 2012 |volume=16 |issue=1 |page=64 |doi=10.4103/0973-029X.92976 |pmid=22438645 |pmc=3303526 }}</ref>. Even though several risk factors have been linked to cleft palates, more research much be done in order to determine the true causes of the defect.\n\n===Palatal abscess===\nPalatal [[abscess]]es may also occur.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Houston |first1=GD |last2=Brown |first2=FH |title=Differential diagnosis of the palatal mass. |journal=Compendium (Newtown, Pa.) |date=October 1993 |volume=14 |issue=10 |pages=1222-4, 1226, 1228-31; quiz 1232 |pmid=8118828}}</ref>\n\n=== Hard palate pigmentation ===\nLong-term use of the drug [[chloroquine]] diphosphatase, used in [[malaria prophylaxis]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and other conditions, was found to cause bluish - grey pigmentation in the hard palate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manger|first=Karin|last2=von Streitberg|first2=Ulrich|last3=Seitz|first3=Gerhard|last4=Kleyer|first4=Arnd|last5=Manger|first5=Bernhard|date=2017-11-28|title=Hard Palate Hyperpigmentation-a Rare Side Effect of Antimalarials|journal=Arthritis & Rheumatology|language=en|volume=70|issue=1|pages=152|doi=10.1002/art.40327|pmid=28941224|issn=2326-5191|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Andrade|first=Bruno-Augusto-Benevenuto|last2=Padron-Alvarado|first2=Nelson-Alejandro|last3=Mu\u00f1oz-Campos|first3=Edgar-Manuel|last4=Morais|first4=Thayn\u00e1-Melo-de Lima|last5=Martinez-Pedraza|first5=Ricardo|date=2017-12-01|title=Hyperpigmentation of hard palate induced by chloroquine therapy|journal=Journal of Clinical and Experimental Dentistry|volume=9|issue=12|pages=e1487\u2013e1491|doi=10.4317/jced.54387|issn=1989-5488|pmc=5794129|pmid=29410767}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Electropalatograph]]\n* [[Head and neck anatomy]]\n* [[Maxilla]]\n* [[Palate]]\n* [[Soft palate]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<br />\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Mouth anatomy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hard Palate}}\n[[Category:Palate]]\n[[Category:Human mouth anatomy|palate]]\n[[Category:Speech organs]]\n\n[[ja:\u53e3\u84cb#\u786c\u53e3\u84cb]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox anatomy\n| Name        = Hard palate\n| Latin       = palatum durum\n| Image       = Illu mouth.jpg\n| Caption     = Mouth (oral cavity)\n| Image2      = Blausen_0872_UpperRespiratorySystem.png\n| Caption2    = Upper respiratory system, with hard palate labeled at right.\n| Precursor   =\n| System      =\n| Artery      = [[greater palatine artery]]\n| Vein        =\n| Nerve       = [[greater palatine nerve]], [[nasopalatine nerve]]\n| Lymph       =\n}}\n\nThe '''hard palate''' is a thin horizontal [[bone|bony]] plate made up of two bones of the [[facial skeleton]], located in the roof of the mouth. The bones are the [[palatine process of the maxilla]] and the [[horizontal plate of palatine bone]]. The hard palate spans the [[alveolar process|alveolar arch]] formed by the [[alveolar process]] that holds the upper [[teeth]] (when these are developed).\n\n==Structure==\nThe hard palate is formed by the [[palatine process of the maxilla]] and [[horizontal plate of palatine bone]]. It forms a partition between the nasal passages and the [[mouth]]. On the anterior portion of the hard palate are the plicae, irregular ridges in the mucous membrane that help facilitate the movement of food backward towards the larynx. This partition is continued deeper into the mouth by a fleshy extension called the [[soft palate]].\n\n==Function==\nThe hard palate is important for feeding and speech. Mammals with a defective hard palate may die shortly after birth due to inability to suckle (see [[#Cleft palate|Cleft palate]] below). It is also involved in [[mastication]] in many species. The interaction between the [[tongue]] and the hard palate is essential in the formation of certain [[Speech communication|speech]] sounds, notably [[palatal consonant]]s such as {{IPA|/j/}} and /t/\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Cleft palate===\nIn the [[birth defect]] called [[cleft palate]], the left and right portions of this plate are not joined, forming a gap between the mouth and nasal passage (a related defect affecting the face is [[cleft lip]]).\n\nWhile a cleft palate has a severe impact upon the ability to [[lactation|nurse]] and speak, it is now successfully treated through reconstructive [[surgery|surgical]] procedures at an early age. This is the time where such procedures are available.\n\nDue to the complexity of this birth defect, researchers still do not know exactly what causes the cleft palate to develop during human development. Recently, these researchers found that even though there is no exact cause, there are several risk factors that drastically increase the risk of a baby being born with an orofacial cleft palate. As for the environmental risk factors, maternal smoking is the most influential risk factor. Based on a recent study of 103 German patients with cleft palates, it was found that 25.2% of them developed the defect due to excessive maternal smoking during pregnancy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reiter |first1=Rudolf |last2=Brosch |first2=Sibylle |last3=Luedeke |first3=Manuel |last4=Fischbein |first4=Elena |last5=Haase |first5=S |last6=Pickhard |first6=A |last7=Assum |first7=G |last8=Schwandt |first8=A |last9=Vogel |first9=W |last10=Maier |first10=C |last11=Hogel |first11=J |title=Genetic and Environmental Risk Factors for Submucous Cleft Palate. |journal=European Journal of Oral Sciences |date=April 2012 |volume=120 |issue=2 |page=97 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0722.2012.00948.x |pmid=22409215 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/221695097 |accessdate=23 November 2019 |ref=4}}</ref> \n\nWhile maternal smoking during pregnancy is a risk, there are also several genetic risk factors. Five SNP variants in the PAX7 gene affect development of facial features.<ref name=Lud2012/> These variations occur at six [[Locus (genetics) | loci]]: 1p36, 2p21, 3p11.1, 8q21.3, 13q31.1 and 15q22.<ref name=Lud2012/> When tested in the European and Asian communities, these loci tests had a 95% acceptance rate.<ref name=Lud2012>{{cite journal |last1=Ludwig |first1=KU |last2=Mangold |first2=E |last3=Herms |first3=S |last4=Nowak |first4=S |last5=Reutter |first5=H |last6=Paul |first6=A |last7=Becker |first7=J |last8=Herberz |first8=R |last9=AlChawa |first9=T |last10=Nasser |first10=E |last11=Bohmer |first11=AC |last12=Mattheisen |first12=M |last13=Alblas |first13=MA |last14=Barth |first14=S |last15=Kluck |first15=N |last16=Lauster |first16=C |last17=Braumann |first17=B |last18=Reich |first18=RH |last19=Hemprich |first19=A |last20=P\u00f6tzsch |first20=S |last21=Blaumeiser |first21=B |last22=Daratsianos |first22=N |last23=Kreusch |first23=T |last24=Murray |first24=JC |last25=Marazita |first25=ML |last26=Ruczinski |first26=I |last27=Scott |first27=AF |last28=Beaty |first28=TH |last29=Kramer |first29=FJ |last30=Wienker |first30=TF |last31=Steegers-Theunissen |first31=RP |last32=Rubini |first32=M |last33=Mossey |first33=PA |last34=Hoffman |first34=P |last35=Lange |first35=C |last36=Chichon |first36=S |last37=Propping |first37=P |last38=Knapp |first38=M |last39=Nothen |first39=MM |title=Genome-wide meta-analyses of nonsyndromic cleft lip with or without cleft palate identify six new risk loci. |journal=Nat Genet |date=Aug 5, 2012 |volume=44 |issue=9 |page=968 |doi=10.1038/ng.2360 |pmid=22863734 |pmc=3598617 }}</ref>. Besides the PAX 7 gene variants, there were also five possible mutations found in the transforming growth factor- alpha gene or TGFA gene that can lead to the development of a cleft palate <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kohli |first1=Sarvraj Singh |last2=Kohli |first2=Virinder Singh |title=A comprehensive review of the genetic basis of cleft lip and palate |journal=Journal of Oral and Maxillofacial Pathology |date=Jan 2012 |volume=16 |issue=1 |page=64 |doi=10.4103/0973-029X.92976 |pmid=22438645 |pmc=3303526 }}</ref>. Even though several risk factors have been linked to cleft palates, more research much be done in order to determine the true causes of the defect.\n\n===Palatal abscess===\nPalatal [[abscess]]es may also occur.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Houston |first1=GD |last2=Brown |first2=FH |title=Differential diagnosis of the palatal mass. |journal=Compendium (Newtown, Pa.) |date=October 1993 |volume=14 |issue=10 |pages=1222-4, 1226, 1228-31; quiz 1232 |pmid=8118828}}</ref>\n\n=== Hard palate pigmentation ===\nLong-term use of the drug [[chloroquine]] diphosphatase, used in [[malaria prophylaxis]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and other conditions, was found to cause bluish - grey pigmentation in the hard palate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manger|first=Karin|last2=von Streitberg|first2=Ulrich|last3=Seitz|first3=Gerhard|last4=Kleyer|first4=Arnd|last5=Manger|first5=Bernhard|date=2017-11-28|title=Hard Palate Hyperpigmentation-a Rare Side Effect of Antimalarials|journal=Arthritis & Rheumatology|language=en|volume=70|issue=1|pages=152|doi=10.1002/art.40327|pmid=28941224|issn=2326-5191|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Andrade|first=Bruno-Augusto-Benevenuto|last2=Padron-Alvarado|first2=Nelson-Alejandro|last3=Mu\u00f1oz-Campos|first3=Edgar-Manuel|last4=Morais|first4=Thayn\u00e1-Melo-de Lima|last5=Martinez-Pedraza|first5=Ricardo|date=2017-12-01|title=Hyperpigmentation of hard palate induced by chloroquine therapy|journal=Journal of Clinical and Experimental Dentistry|volume=9|issue=12|pages=e1487\u2013e1491|doi=10.4317/jced.54387|issn=1989-5488|pmc=5794129|pmid=29410767}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Electropalatograph]]\n* [[Head and neck anatomy]]\n* [[Maxilla]]\n* [[Palate]]\n* [[Soft palate]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<br />\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Mouth anatomy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hard Palate}}\n[[Category:Palate]]\n[[Category:Human mouth anatomy|palate]]\n[[Category:Speech organs]]\n\n[[ja:\u53e3\u84cb#\u786c\u53e3\u84cb]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:587:590d:3c00:a89b